system.description:
• Damage Resistance

    • Lightning Damage

  • Natural Scale Armor

    • Parts of your skin are covered by a thin sheen of dragon-like scales.

      • When you aren’t wearing armor, your AC equals 13 + your Dexterity modifier. (Already Applied)

  • Undermountain Vision

    • Dark Vision up to 60 feet.

• Ability Score Modifier (Already Applied)

    • Although Dragonborn grew to hate dragons, you are distantly related to blue chromatic dragons

      • Increase your Constitution Ability Score by 2 and your Charisma Ability Score by 1.

• You can use your action to exhale destructive Lightning Energy in a 5' by 30' line.

    • When you use your breath weapon, all creatures in the area must make a Dexterity saving throw.

      • The DC of this saving throw is 8 + your Constitution modifier + your proficiency bonus.

      • A creature takes 2d6 Lightning damage on a failed save.

      • On a save, they talk half as much damage.

Includes:

  • 1x Backpack

  • 1x Bedroll

  • 1x Mess Tin

  • 1x Tinderbox

  • 10x Torch

  • 10x Rations (1 Supply)

  • 1x Waterskin

  • 1x Rope, Hempen (50 Feet)

Loading, Range (80/320), Simple, Two-Handed

1d8 + @dex.mod Piercing Damage
A bundle of 20 bolts.
Dual-Wielding, Finesse, Simple

• Spell Slots

    • The Unstable Sorcery Class Table shows how many spell slots you have to cast your sorcerer spells of 1st level and higher.

      • To cast one of these sorcerer spells, you must expend a slot of the spell's level or higher.

        • For example, if you know the 1st-level spell burning hands and have a 1st-level and a 2nd-level spell slot available, you can cast burning hands using either slot.

        • You regain all expended spell slots when you finish a long rest.

  • Spells Known

    • You start knowing 2 spells from the Sorcerer Spell List, and you learn more at certain levels as shown in the Spells Known column of the Unstable Sorcerer Class Table.

      • https://www.dndbeyond.com/spells/class/sorcerer

    • These spells are engraved into your very being and as such, are hard to change.

      • Whenever you gain a level in this class, you may choose one of the sorcerer spells you know and replace it with another spell from the sorcerer spell list, which still must be of a level you can cast.

  • Spells Casting Ability

    • Charisma is your spellcasting ability for your sorcerer spells, since the power of your magic relies on your ability to project your will into the world.

      • You use Charisma whenever a spell refers to your spellcasting ability.

      • In addition, you use your Charisma modifier when setting the saving throw DC for a sorcerer spell you cast and when making an attack roll with one.

        • Spell save DC = 8 + your proficiency bonus + your Charisma modifier

        • Spell attack modifier = your proficiency bonus + your Charisma modifier

• You may use an Arcane Focus as a spellcasting focus for your sorcerer spells.

    • Fire and Lightning Specialty

      • When holding an Arcane Focus, Lightning and Fire spells and Manifestations are amplified one level higher than the level at which they were cast.

    • Additionally, you have resistance to Fire damage even if an Arcane Focus is not equipped.

• Beginning at 2nd level, you have begun to tap into an inner wellspring of magic.

    • This wellspring is represented by Sorcery Points, which allows you to produce a variety of magical effects.

      • Your total number of Sorcery Points is equal to three times your Sorcerer level (This number can be seen in the Sorcery Points column in the Unstable Sorcerer Class Table) and you recover all expended sorcery points upon completing a long rest.

      • Instead of expending spell slots, you may use Sorcery Points to cast a Sorcerer spell you know.

        • You expend a number of Sorcery Points equal to twice the spells level and you cast it as if you had expended a spell slot of the appropriate level.

          • You cannot use Sorcery Points to cast a spell of a level higher than your proficiency bonus.

          • You may not upcast spells cast through this method.

• At 2nd level, at the start of your turn, No Action required, you may enter a state known as Overloaded.

    • Overloaded

      • You have advantage on checks made to maintain concentration on a Sorcerer spell.

      • If you cast a spell that affects an area around you, if the area is smaller than your Manifestation range, it is now the same as your Manifestation range.

      • If you cast a spell with a range of touch, you may target any creature within your Manifestation range.

    • This lasts for a number of rounds equal to your Constitution Modifier or until you fall unconscious.

      • Once you leave Overload, you are unable to enter it again until twice the number of turns it was active.

    • Unstable

      • You have disadvantage on attacks made with weapons while your body literally vibrates with energy.

      • You must roll a D20 any time you cast a spell while Overloaded and take the following effect.

        • 1-5: The spell duplicates but the DM gains control of it.

        • 6-14: The spell does what it’s meant to and you have control over it.

        • 15-20: The spell duplicates and you have control over it.

• At 3rd level, you can whisper an ancient word into a spell cast by an ally or enemy that you can see as they cast it.

    • You must burn a spell slot of equal value or greater to manipulate their magic in this way.

      • Discuss with the DM briefly if something is allowed, but have fun with this.

    • Examples of this:

      • You may whisper the ancient words for an element to add that type of damage to their attack.

      • Add healing to a spell that was originally only meant to push or pull or damage.

      • Add cleansing abilities to heal someone of poison when they’re healed of something else as well.

      • Have a spell backfire or find a new target.

• Upon reaching 3rd level, you’ve spent a lot of time with Mogli and Corrosis, these spells are now part of your Known Spells without taking up your Known Spell slots.

    • 1st Level

      • Burning Hands

      • Hellish Rebuke

    • 3rd Level

      • Flaming Sphere

      • Pyrotechnics

    • 5th Level

      • Ashardalon's Stride

      • Fireball (Leveled Up)

    • 7th Level

      • Fire Shield

      • Wall of Fire

    • 9th Level

      • Flame Strike

      • Immolation

• You innately know spells that flow through your blue Dragonborn blood, therefore these spells are part of your Known Spells without taking up Known Spell slots.

    • 1st Level

      • Witch Bolt

      • Absorb Elements

      • Chromatic Orb (Must Choose Lightning unless you make it one of your Known Spell Slots)

    • 3rd Level

      • Alter Self

      • Lightning Arrow

      • Fireball

    • 5th Level

      • Call Lightning

      • Lightning Bolt

    • 7th Level

      • Storm Sphere

      • Polymorph

    • 9th Level

      • Destructive Wave

      • Summon Draconic Spirit

• At 1st level While touching a flammable object (Such as cloth or a piece of tinder) you may use your bonus action to ignite it.

    • The object you touch must be able to fit within a 5- feet cube.

• At 1st level, unlike most casters, Sorcerers are infused with the arcane and are not limited to mere cantrips and thus gain abilities known as Arcane Manifestations.

    • Groa Manifestations, Metamagics, & Combat Traits.docx

    • You begin with 3 Arcane Manifestations found here:

    • You learn new Arcane Manifestations at the levels stated in the Unstable Sorcery Class Table.

    • Additionally, your magic emanates out from you, shining an unnatural blue starlight that gives away your primary Manifestation Range.

      • Both your allies and enemies can see this light and will catch on to its purpose.

More Detailed Break Down of Arcane Manifestations Below:

  • Groa gains a special feature in place of cantrips known as Arcane Manifestations.
    • They are considered spells, specifically Level 0 Spells (Like cantrips).
    • However, they differ in the following ways:
      • At the beginning of your turn, before taking any other actions or movement, you may use Manifestations without using actions.
      • Manifestations can not be used if you’re incapacitated, or something is restricting you from casting.
      • Manifestations don't require somatic or verbal components.
        • However there are identifying signals to indicate you are using one, such as your eyes glowing.
          • The signal is described in each Manifestation description.
          • This signal can not be hidden-and a creature who sees the signal can attempt to counterspell the Manifestation.
        • The DC to counterspell a Manifestation is equal to your Spell save DC.
        • Creatures always need to make an ability check in order to counter your Manifestation.
        • Manifestations do not scale off level like regular cantrips.
          • Instead, you may expend Sorcery Points to empower them.
        • Empowered effects for a Manifestation can be found in each Manifestation description.
          • When empowering a Manifestation, you cannot expend more Sorcery Points than an amount equal to your Sorcerer level.
        • Manifestations will refer to your Manifestation Range, which represents the area in which the Manifestation can affect.
          • This range is most often a 15-foot radius around you.
          • Some sorcerer features may improve this range beyond the normal 15-feet.

KgmqUoxp1nFJkG8P.description:
Burning Focus Empowerment

  • Type: Evocation

  • Signal: You exhale a blue crackling mist into your palm.

  • You release a miniature bolt of electricity into two creatures within your Manifestation Range, causing 1d4 lightning damage.

  • Empowered: For every sorcery point expended to empower this Manifestation, you release an additional bolt.

    • These bolts can target the same creature, or different ones within range.

system.description:
• At 3rd level, you have an innate Manifestation not mentioned on the Arcane Manifestations document, connecting you further with the chaos of lightning. 

    • High Voltage Manifestation

      • This is affected by any abilities or features that refer to Manifestations.

      • Type: Evocation

      • Signal: You exhale a blue crackling mist into your palm.

      • You release a miniature bolt of electricity into a creature within your Manifestation Range, causing 1d4 lightning damage.

      • Empowered: For every sorcery point expended to empower this Manifestation, you release an additional bolt.

        • These bolts can target the same creature, or different ones within range.

iihaT4sDdFMlKu9H.name: Create Flame (Focus)
iihaT4sDdFMlKu9H.description:
Burning Focus Empowerment

  • You ignite flame in a space within your doubled Manifestation Range, causing magical fire to appear within a 5-foot swirling flame within that doubled Manifestation Range, and another within your regular Manifestation Range.

    • Creatures who touch it must succeed on a Dexterity saving throw or suffer 1d8 fire damage on a failed Dexterity saving throw.

      • If they save then they take half damage.

    • The fire remains until it is no longer within your doubled Manifestation Range or is detonated by a creature it touches.

  • Empowered: For every sorcery point expended to empower this Manifestation, you may create an additional 5-foot swirling flame within your normal Manifestation Range.

    • Each separate cube provokes a save for creatures touching them.

system.description:
• At 2nd level, at the start of your turn, No Action required, you may enter a state known as Overloaded and Unstable.

    • Overloaded

      • You have advantage on checks made to maintain concentration on a Sorcerer spell.

      • If you cast a spell that affects an area around you, if the area is smaller than your Manifestation Range, it is now the same as your Manifestation Range.

      • If you cast a spell with a range of touch, you may target any creature within your Manifestation Range.

    • This lasts for a number of rounds equal to your Constitution Modifier or until you fall unconscious.

      • Once you leave Overload, you are unable to enter it again until twice the number of turns it was active.

    • Unstable

      • You have disadvantage on attacks made with weapons while your body literally vibrates with energy.

      • You must roll a D20 any time you cast a spell while Overloaded and take the following effect.

        • 1-5: The spell duplicates but the DM gains control of it.

        • 6-14: The spell does what it’s meant to and you have control over it.

        • 15-20: The spell duplicates and you have control over it.

• At 3rd level, your connection to magic has revealed special secrets known as Metamagics, starting with 2 and gaining more through other features.

    • Metamagics Found Here:

      • Groa Manifestations, Metamagics, & Combat Traits.docx

    • If a Metamagic can be applied to a spell, you can only apply one Metamagic to the spell (Unless otherwise stated in the Metamagics description)

    • You do not naturally learn new Metamagics, however you are able to learn more through the Arcanic Specialization and the Secrets of Magic features you possess.

    • Whenever you gain a level in this class, you may exchange one Metamagic you know for another, unless otherwise stated.

More Details Below:

  • Metamagic options augment your spells upon reaching 3rd level.
  • You start knowing two and learn more as you gain levels in this class.
  • When applying a Metamagic to a spell, you can only apply one Metamagic to that particular spell.
    • That is, unless an ability or feature says otherwise.

• Upon reaching 3rd level, you have unearthed even more arcane secrets allowing you to choose a number of Combat Traits equal to the number mentioned in the Unstable Sorcerer Class Table.

    • Combat Traits Found Here:

      • Groa Manifestations, Metamagics, & Combat Traits.docx

    • Some features have a level prerequisite, in order to choose that feature, you must have at least that many levels in the Sorcerer class.

  • Upon reaching the following levels in this class, you may select an additional Combat Trait that you meet the prerequisites for: 9th Level, 15th level, 21st level, 27th level.

• At Level 3, Corrosis has taught you how to redirect another caster’s spell while you and the other caster are within your Manifestation Range.

    • You begin by readying an action, preparing to catch and redirect a spell cast by another.

      • Once a spell is cast you may trigger your action and concentrate on the spell as long as you have the appropriate number of spell slots required to cast it yourself.

        • If the other caster is willing, this is considered amplifying the spell by 1 level, however you gain control of it (AKA, you land the plane)

        • If the caster resists you, a Spellcasting Contest erupts between you and the other caster.

          • They must defeat a Charisma Spell casting save + your Spell Casting Modifier.

    • You cannot stop a spell from being cast with this ability.

      • Your best option is to redirect it.

    • Additionally, you may add your Known Metamagics as well, so long as you follow the requirements detailed in its description.

    • If it's a fire or lightning spell and you are using a focus, then your Burning Focus applies as per usual.

      • DM Note 1: If I don’t plan to have my monsters cast a spell, I’m not going to change my plans to make this work.

        • You may waste your action doing this.

          • However, I won’t avoid doing so either if that was my original plan and I believe that character would do so not realizing you have this ability.

            • The likelihood of it happening twice to the same caster who you’ve used it on without them preparing to stop you is slim to none.

      • DM Note 2: You have a team of random casters, so if they know you readied your action and can amplify their magic, they’ll likely try to make that happen.

        • Again, they may not and you may waste an action, and therefore this should be used strategically.

system.description:
Corrosis has taught you how to cast this spell as a reaction at 5th level and above.

A bright streak flashes from your pointing finger to a point you
choose within range then blossoms with a low roar into an
explosion of flame.


Each creature in a 20-foot radius must make a Dexterity saving
throw. A target takes 10d6 fire damage on a failed save, or half as
much damage on a successful one. The fire spreads around
corners. It ignites flammable objects in the area that aren’t being
worn or carried.


At higher level: The damage increases by 1d6 for each slot level above 5th.

system.description:
• A 5-foot-diameter sphere of fire appears in an unoccupied space of your choice within range and lasts for the duration.
    • Any creature that ends its turn within 5 feet of the sphere must make a Dexterity saving throw.
      • The creature takes 3d6 fire damage on a failed save, or half as much damage on a successful one.
        • As a bonus action, you can move the sphere up to 30 feet.
          • If you ram the sphere into a creature, that creature must make the saving throw against the sphere’s damage, and the sphere stops moving this turn.
          • When you move the sphere, you can direct it over barriers up to 5 feet tall and jump it across pits up to 10 feet wide.
            • The sphere ignites flammable objects not being worn or carried, and it sheds bright light in a 20-foot radius and dim light for an additional 20 feet. 

 

At higher level: The damage increases by 1d6 for each slot level above 3rd.

The spell deals an additional 1d6 fire damage for each slot level above 5th.

The billowing flames of a dragon blast from your feet, granting you explosive speed. For the duration, your speed increases by 30 feet and moving doesn’t provoke opportunity attacks.

When you move within 5 feet of a creature or an object that isn’t being worn or carried, it takes 3d6 fire damage from your trail of heat. A creature or object can take this damage only once during a turn.

At Higher Levels. Increase your speed by 5 feet for each spell slot level above 5th. The spell deals an additional 1d6 fire damage for each slot level above 5th.

 

Source: Fizban's Treasury of Dragons

system.description:
Evocation

Level: 7
Casting time: 1 Action
Range: Self
Components: V, S, M (a bit of phosphorus or a firefly)
Duration: 1 hour

Corrosis has taught you how to cast this spell as a reaction at 7th level and above.

Until the spell ends, flames envelop your body, casting bright light in a 10-foot radius and dim light for an additional 10 feet. You can use an action to end the spell early by using an action.

Choose one of the following options:

  • Chill Shield: You have resistance to fire damage. A creature within 5 feet of you takes 2d8 cold damage when it hits you with a melee attack.

  • Warm Shield: You have resistance to cold damage. A creature within 5 feet of you takes 2d8 fire damage when it hits you with a melee attack.

Cast at Higher Levels. The duration increases to 8 hours when using an 8th-level spell slot.

Source: Elemental Evil spell

Evocation

Level: 9
Casting time: 1 Action
Range: 90 feet
Components: V
Duration: Up to 5 minute

 

Flames wreathe one creature you can see within range. The target must make a Dexterity saving throw. It takes 8d6 fire damage on a failed save, or half as much damage on a successful one. On a failed save, the target also burns for the spell’s duration. The burning target sheds bright light in a 30-foot radius and dim light for an additional 30 feet. If damage from this spell kills a target, the target is turned to ash.

 

Cast at Higher Levels: Duration lasts 1 minute longer on a target's failed save for each level of spell cast over level 5.

system.description:
Choose two areas of nonmagical flame that you can see and that fits within a 5-foot cube within range. You can extinguish the fire in that area, and you create either fireworks or smoke when you do so.

Fireworks: The target explodes with a dazzling display of colors. Each creature within 10 feet of the target must succeed on a Constitution saving throw or become blinded until the end of your next turn.

Smoke: Thick black smoke spreads out from the target in a 20-foot radius, moving around corners. The area of the smoke is heavily obscured. The smoke persists for 1 minute or until a strong wind disperses it.

 

At higher level: When you cast this spell using a spell slot of 4th level or higher, the number of targets increase by 1.

 

Source: Elemental Evil Spell Book

system.description:
Evocation

Level: 7th
Casting time: 1 Action
Range: 120 feet
Components: V, S, M (a small piece of phosphorus)
Duration: Concentration, up to 1 minute

Corrosis has taught you how to cast this spell as a reaction at 7th level and above.

You create a wall of fire on a solid surface within range. You can make the wall up to 60 feet long, 20 feet high, and 1 foot thick, or a ringed wall up to 20 feet in diameter, 20 feet high, and 1 foot thick. The wall is opaque and lasts for the duration.

When the wall appears, each creature within its area must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a failed save, a creature takes 8d8 fire damage, or half as much damage on a successful save.

One side of the wall, selected by you when you cast this spell, deals 5d8 fire damage to each creature that ends its turn within 10 feet of that side or inside the wall. A creature takes the same damage when it enters the wall for the first time on a turn or ends its turn there. The other side of the wall deals no damage.

 

At Higher Level: The damage increases by 1d8 for each slot level above 7th.

Level: 1
Casting time: 1 Action
Range: 30 feet
Components: V, S, M (a twig from a tree that has been struck by lightning)
Duration: Concentration, up to 1 minute

 

A beam of crackling, blue energy lances out toward a creature within range, forming a sustained arc of lightning between you and the target.


Make a ranged spell attack against that creature. On a hit, the target takes 1d12 lightning damage, and on each of your turns for the duration, you can use your action to deal 1d12 lightning damage to the target automatically. The spell ends if you use your action to do anything else. The spell also ends if the target is ever outside the spell’s range or if it has total cover from you.

 

At Higher Levels: The initial damage increases by 1d12 for each slot level above 1st.

• A creature can use its action to eat one berry.

• Type: Necromancy

  • Signal: Tendrils of necrotic smoke stretch out toward those surrounding you.

  • You drain life essence from those around you, dealing 1 necrotic damage to all creatures within your Manifestation Range.

    • For each creature that suffers this damage, you gain 1 temporary hit point.

      • These temporary hit points stack with other temporary hit points.

  • Empowered: For every Sorcery Point expended to empower this Manifestation, you multiply the damage caused and temporary hit points gained by + 1 (Spending 1 point would multiply the temp HP by 2, spending 2 would multiply it by 3, etc…)

• Type: Enchantment

  • Signal: Your eyes appear bloodshot as they turn a nearly black crimson.

  • All creatures of your choice within your Manifestation Range whose current hit points are 5 or less become wracked with pain, suffering a penalty to all ability checks, attack rolls and saving throws they make until the start of your next turn.

  • Empowered: For every Sorcery Point expended to empower this Manifestation, the hit point limit is increased by 5.

    • For example, if you expended 3 Sorcery Points, this would now affect creatures whose current hit points are 20 or less

• Your Manifestation Range is increased by 15-feet.

  • You may select this feature multiple times, increasing your range appropriately.

• Type: Transmutation

  • Signal: Eyes pulse with a white glow.

  • You assert minor telekinetic control over the world around you.

    • You may take the Use an Object action on an object within your Manifestation Range (Such as opening an unlocked door, pulling a level, pressing a button, or even feeding yourself a potion)

  • Empowered: For every Sorcery Point expended to empower this Manifestation, you may instead move an unattended object within your Manifestation Range.

    • The weight limit for this is a number of pounds equal to 5 times the number of Sorcery Points expended.

system.description:
• If you are able to make multiple attacks with the Attack action, this maneuver replaces one of them.
  • You may use your Disarm maneuver to attempt to knock an item or weapon from a creature's hand.
    • The target must be within your reach and be holding an item (either carried or wielded).
      • The target makes a Strength or Dexterity saving throw against your maneuver DC.
        • The target has advantage if it is larger than you or holding the item with two or more hands
        • Alternatively, a target smaller than you has disadvantage.
          • On a failure, you deal basic melee damage and the target drops the item in its space.

• Allows a character to evade opportunity attacks for the rest of their turn.
    • It’s a defensive tactic used when you want to safely move away from an enemy without risking a free swing.

• While you cannot grapple a creature two or more size categories larger than you, you can grab onto it.
    • By jumping onto its back or climbing up a limb, you can make a Strength or Dexterity saving throw against the creature's maneuver DC to cling to or balance upon its body.
      • On a success, you move into the creature's space and can move upon its body as if it is difficult terrain.
  • While grabbing onto a larger creature, you gain advantage on attack rolls against it.
    • The larger creature may be able to attack you as normal, depending on its limbs or attacks.
      • It can also use an action or replace one of its attacks on its turn to try to dislodge you, such as shaking you loose or bashing you against a wall, forcing you to make a Strength or Dexterity saving throw against its maneuver DC or fall prone into the nearest space adjacent to the creature, taking its basic melee damage in the process.
  • If the creature chooses to roll over in order to dislodge you, it becomes prone, but you have disadvantage on the saving throw to hang on.

• If you are able to make multiple attacks with the Attack action, this maneuver replaces one of them.
  • You can use the Grapple maneuver to grab or wrestle a creature
    • You must have at least one free hand to attempt a grapple, your target must be within your reach, and the target must be no more than one size category larger than you.
      • The target makes a Strength or Dexterity saving throw against your maneuver DC.
        • On a failure, you deal basic melee damage and the target becomes grappled.
          • In addition to things that end the condition, you can release the target at any time (no action required).
  • Escaping a Grapple
    • While grappled, a creature can use its action to attempt to escape. It must succeed on a Strength or Dexterity saving throw against your maneuver DC.
  • Moving a Grappled Creature
    • When you move, you can drag or carry the grappled creature with you.
      • When you do so, your Speed is halved, unless the creature's weight is within your carrying capacity and you are not encumbered by bulky items.
  • Freeing a Grappled Creature
    • You can use the Grapple maneuver to try to free another grappled or restrained creature.
      • The creature grappling or restraining the target makes a Strength saving throw against your maneuver DC.
        • If it fails the saving throw, the grappled or restrained creature is freed.
        • Additionally, you may move the freed creature 5 feet in any direction.

• If you are able to make multiple attacks with the Attack action, this maneuver replaces one of them.
  • You can use the Knockdown maneuver to trip or push a creature down.
    • The target must be within your reach and be no more than one size category larger than you.
    • The target makes a Strength saving throw against your maneuver DC.
      • On a failure, you deal basic melee damage and knock the target prone.

• You can use an action or bonus action to make an Overrun maneuver to move through a hostile creature's space by forcing your way past.
    • Make a Strength saving throw against the target's maneuver DC.
      • On a success, you deal basic melee damage and can move through the hostile creature's space once this turn.
      • The creature can choose to let you pass instead of rolling.
      • You have advantage if you are larger than the target, or disadvantage if you are smaller.
      • If you are two or more sizes smaller than the target, you can move through the hostile creature's space without making a save.
      • You still provoke opportunity attacks if you move beyond a creature's reach.

• If you are able to make multiple attacks with the Attack action, this maneuver replaces one of them.
  • You can use the Shove maneuver to push a creature away.
    • The target must be within your reach and be no more than one size category larger than you.
      • The target makes a Strength saving throw against your maneuver DC.
        • On a failure, you deal basic melee damage and push the target a number of feet away from you equal to 5 + 5 for every 5 points it failed its saving throw by.
          • You can move the creature in any direction away from you (to the side, forward, or diagonally away).
    • A creature that is shoved off of a precipice is propelled off of whatever it is standing on -- it does not receive any saving throw or ability check to grab onto something to avoid falling down below.

Each creature in a 20-foot radius must make a Dexterity saving
throw. A target takes 8d6 fire damage on a failed save, or half as
much damage on a successful one. The fire spreads around

At higher level: The damage increases by 1d6 for each slot level above 3rd.

• You attempt to interrupt a creature in the process of casting a spell.
    • If the creature is casting a spell of 3rd level or lower, its spell fails and has no effect.
      • If it is casting a spell of 4th level or higher, make an ability check using your spellcasting ability.
        • The DC equals 10 + the spell’s level.
          • On a success, the creature’s spell fails and has no effect.
  • At Higher Levels:
    • When you cast this spell using a spell slot of 4th level or higher, the interrupted spell has no effect if its level is less than or equal to the level of the spell slot you used.
      • If the spell being countered is one level higher than the spell slot used to cast Counterspell, make an ability check using your spellcasting ability.
        • The DC equals 10 + the spell’s level.
          • On a success, the creature’s spell fails and has no effect.

system.description:
• As a reaction, this spell captures some of the incoming energy, lessening its effect on you and storing it for your next melee attack.
    • You have resistance to the triggering damage type until the start of your next turn.
      • The first time you hit with a melee attack on your next turn, the target takes an extra 1d6 damage of the triggering type, and the spell ends.
      • Gaining resistence to a damage you already have resistence to does not gain Immunity from that damage via this spell. 
        • However, the first time you hit with a melee attack on your next turn, the target still takes an extra 1d6 damage of the triggering type.
        • Gróa Note: If you are using a focus, the damage of your fire or lightning goes up 1d6 higher as though you'd cast the spell at the next level. 

At Higher Levels. When you cast this spell using a spell slot of 2nd level or higher, the extra damage increases by 1d6 for each slot level above 1st.

Source: Elemental Evil Player's Companion

You create a wall of fire on a solid surface within range. You can make the wall up to 60 feet long, 20 feet high, and 1 foot thick, or a ringed wall up to 20 feet in diameter, 20 feet high, and 1 foot thick. The wall is opaque and lasts for the duration.

When the wall appears, each creature within its area must make a Dexterity saving throw. On a failed save, a creature takes 5d8 fire damage, or half as much damage on a successful save.

One side of the wall, selected by you when you cast this spell, deals 5d8 fire damage to each creature that ends its turn within 10 feet of that side or inside the wall. A creature takes the same damage when it enters the wall for the first time on a turn or ends its turn there. The other side of the wall deals no damage.

At Higher Levels. When you cast this spell using a spell slot of 5th level or higher, the damage increases by 1d8 for each slot level above 4th.

Until the spell ends, you automatically sense the presence of magic within range, and you can use an action to study the aura of a magic effect to learn its schools of magic (if any).

The spell penetrates most barriers but is blocked by 3 feet of wood or dirt, 1 foot of stone, 1 inch of common metal, or a thin sheet of lead.

Cast at Higher Levels. When using a 2nd-level spell slot or higher, the spell no longer requires your concentration. When using a 3rd-level spell slot or higher, the duration increases to 1 hour. When using a 4th-level spell slot or higher, the duration increases to 8 hours.

• Taking the Dash action gives you additional movement, equal to your speed, for the current turn.
    • For a creature with a walking speed of 30ft, this means their movement for that turn would increase to 60ft.
      • This bonus includes any modifiers to your speed
      • This also applies to negative modifiers
      • Note: A situation that often causes confusion is when you Dash after standing up from being prone, which costs half of your movement.
        • Creatures with 30ft speed who are standing up from being knocked prone only has 15ft of movement remaining, but Dash doubles the original 30ft, and therefore they can move 45ft after getting up from being knocked prone.

• When you take the Dodge action, you focus entirely on avoiding attacks.
    • Until the start of your next turn, any attack roll made against you has disadvantage if you can see the attacker.
    • Additionally, you make Dexterity saving throws with advantage.
    • Note: You lose these benefits if you are incapacitated or if your speed drops to 0.

• Instead of using a weapon to make a melee weapon attack, you can use an unarmed strike: a punch, kick, head-butt, or similar forceful blow (none of which count as weapons).
    • On a hit, an Unarmed Strike deals bludgeoning damage equal to 1 + your Strength modifier.
      • You are proficient with your unarmed strikes.
      • This damage cannot be halved by a saving throw.

A component pouch is a small, watertight leather belt pouch that has compartments to hold all the material components and other special items you need to cast your spells, except for those components that have a specific cost (as indicated in a spell‚Äôs description).

A trio of glowing darts of magical force unerringly and simultaneously strike the targets, each dealing 1d4+1 force damage.

Cast at Higher Levels. Evoke one additional dart and target up to one additional creature for each slot level above 1st.

Until the spell ends, the target is protected by a shimmering magical force. Its AC becomes 13 + its Dexterity modifier. The spell ends if the target dons armor, or if you use an action to dismiss it.

Cast at Higher Levels. The target gains 5 temporary hit points for each slot level above 1st. The temporary hit points last for the spell's duration.

You use magic to mold yourself into a new form. Choose one of the options below. Until the spell ends, you can use an action to choose a different option.

  • Amphibian: Your body takes on aquatic adaptations. You can breathe underwater normally and gain a swimming speed equal to your base Speed.

  • Altered State: You decide what you look like.

    None of your gameplay statistics change but you can alter anything about your body's appearance, including but not limited to: your heritage, 1 foot of height, weight, clothing, tattoos, piercings, facial features, sound of your voice, hair style and length, skin and eye coloration, sex, and any other distinguishing features. You cannot become a creature of a different size category, and your limb structure remains the same; for example if you're bipedal, you can't use this spell to become a quadruped. Until the spell ends, you can use an action to change your appearance.

  • Red in Tooth and Claw: You grow magical natural weapons of your choice with a +1 bonus to attack and damage. Your unarmed strikes deal 1d6 bludgeoning, piercing, or slashing damage of a type determined by the natural weapon you chose; for example a tentacle deals bludgeoning, a horn deals piercing, and claws deal slashing.

Cast at Higher Levels. When using a spell slot of 5th-level, add the following to the list of forms you can adopt.

  • Greater Natural Weapons: The damage dealt by your natural weapon increases to 2d6, and you gain a +2 bonus to attack and damage rolls with your natural weapons.

  • Mask of the Grave: You adopt the appearance of a skeleton or zombie (your choice). Your type changes to undead, and mindless undead creatures ignore your presence, treating you as one of their own. You don't need to breathe and you become immune to poison.

  • Wings: A pair of wings sprouts from your back. The wings can appear bird-like, leathery like a bat or dragon's wings, or like the wings of an insect. You gain a fly speed equal to your base Speed.

• The next time you make a ranged weapon attack during the spell’s duration, the weapon’s ammunition, or the weapon itself if it’s a thrown weapon, transforms into a bolt of lightning.
    • Make the attack roll as normal.
    • The target takes 4d8 lightning damage on a hit, or half as much damage on a miss, instead of the weapon’s normal damage.
  • Whether you hit or miss, each creature within 10 feet of the target must make a Dexterity saving throw.
    • Each of these creatures takes 2d8 lightning damage on a failed save, or half as much damage on a successful one.
      • The piece of ammunition or weapon then returns to its normal form.

At Higher Levels. When you cast this spell using a spell slot of 4th level or higher, the damage for both effects of the spell increases by 1d8 for each slot level above 3rd.

• You hurl a 4-inch-diameter sphere of energy at a creature that you can see within range.
    • Make a ranged spell attack against the target and lob a Lightning Orb at them.
      • If the attack hits, the creature takes 3d8 Lightning Damage.

At Higher Levels. When you cast this spell using a spell slot of 2nd level or higher, the damage increases by 1d8 for each slot level above 1st.

During a long rest, you can pocket inside of this Arcane Focus a level 1 spell that can be cast freely.

  • The spell cannot require concentration

• An engagement ring that originally belonged to Golgazia, given to him by his secret fiancé.
    • Previously believed to have been stolen from the battlefield, but getting this from her mentor started connecting dots she'd originally not been able to connect about why her Mentor refused to mate despite constantly preaching the need for their species to procreate.
    • Under great need, speaking to the ring may make the dragon form to fall away and a direct communication with Golgazia is opened up to request information or to pray for aide.
      • 1d20
        • 1-6, the connection fails and the dragon doesn't unwrap.
        • 7-12, the connection is weak, but a quick question may be asked.
        • 13-18, the connection is strong and a few questions can be asked.
        • 19-20, the connection is complete and Golgazia steps back into the physical realm for a short time to deliver aide.

system.description: One of the many secrets unveiled about Sevani Dreigh Ude by Mogli is the discovery of how to create Portal Coins for his Elite Warriors. By sacrificing his own life force, one full year to be exact, he can fuse a coin to the blood of one of his Elite. Only the person fused to the coin can use the Portal Coin to return to Sevani Dreigh Ude. These coins can also be used by his Elite to return to Mogli's side, but this can only occur once per day as he does not carry the same amount of power to move creatures across the cosmos as Sevani Dreigh Ude encompasses.

system.description:
• At Level 1, Gróa has spent enough time with Whitaker Black’s Spell Pockets that she’s perfected the art of creating them herself.

    • As an action, she may touch an object and focus her energy to place a spell she has memorized into it, expending a spell slot of equal value or greater in the process.

      • Any creature who shares a bond with Gróa may cast the spell from the Spell Pocket as an action, using their highest stat as their spell modifier.

        • If the spell requires focus, the creature casting it must have the ability to do so via their natural traits.

        • The spell cannot be increased in power unless the creature possesses the ability to naturally increase a spell’s level using their own power.

          • Alternatively, a creature may increase a spell's power if they possess one of Gróa’s Spellpower Banks.

        • The Spell Pocket has one use and returns to its natural state after the spell within has been expended.

      • Fair Warning: When a creature has a Spell Pocket on their person, they become attuned to it and the Spell Pocket grows warm to the touch.

        • If more than two Spell Pockets are within 30 feet of one another, they begin to vibrate and may EXPLODE at any moment, releasing the spell within (DM chooses how and where the spell lands).

        • Additionally, if Gróa is currently Overloaded and Unstable, so, too, are all Spell Pockets she’s created within 30 feet of her.

• At Level 3, Gróa has spent enough time producing Spell Pockets that she’s developed the ability to create Spellpower Banks to increase the power of spells within those Spell Pockets by one level.

    • Any creature who shares a bond with Gróa may use the power stored within these Spellpower Banks to upcast the spell within a Spell Pocket by one level.

      • Alternatively, any spell caster may use these Spellpower Banks to upcast their own spells by one level.

    • Warning: these are full of Gróa’s Unstable spell power and may go off catastrophically when a creature possessing one is struck by a critical hit or they critically fail certain rolls (DM’s Discretion).
